  "summary": "After leaving Mrs. Luton, Colin Lamb reflects on the names \"Rosemary\" and \"Sheila,\" which Mrs. Luton explained were chosen by her sister and named after their mother, respectively. Lamb then travels through the streets near Covent Garden to a crowded, dimly lit bookstore owned by Mr. Solomon near the British Museum. While navigating the bookstore's various floors to research seaweed, ocean biology, and fossils, Lamb passes through a storage area on the second floor before reaching the third floor. There, he encounters a middle-aged woman referred to as \"Nanny,\" who informs him that a man named Mr. Collins is unhappy with his progress.\n\nLamb enters a smoke-filled room to meet Colonel Beck, a group leader. Beck expresses frustration regarding the lack of progress in Lamb's investigation into Wilbraham Crescent. Lamb reports that he has been investigating houses on New Moon Street and shares a discovery: a murder occurred on Wilbraham Crescent, though the victim's identity remains unknown because a business card found in the victim's pocket contained a fake name and address. Lamb requests permission to investigate specific individuals, identifying a house called \"Diana's Cottage\" located at 20 Wilbraham Crescent in Crofton, ten miles from Portbury. He explains that the cottage is inhabited by a Mrs. Hemm, who spends her time caring for eighteen cats.",
